#### Equipment

*   Main article: [List of equipment of the British Army](/List_of_equipment_of_the_British_Army)

##### Infantry

The British Army's basic weapon is the 5.56 mm [L85A2 or L85A3](/SA80) assault rifle, with some specialist personnel using the L22A2 carbine variant (pilots and some tank crew). The weapon was traditionally equipped with either [iron sights](/Iron_sights) or an optical [SUSAT](/SUSAT), although other optical sights have been subsequently purchased to supplement these. &#91;150&#93; The weapon can be enhanced further utilising the [Picatinny rail](/Picatinny_rail) with attachments such as the [L17A2](/L17A2_UGL) under-barrel grenade launcher. &#91;151&#93; In 2023, the [Army Special Operations Brigade](/Army_Special_Operations_Brigade), which includes the [Ranger Regiment](/Ranger_Regiment_(United_Kingdom)), began using the [L403A1](/L403A1), an [AR-pattern](/M16_rifle) rifle also used by the [Royal Marines](/Royal_Marines). &#91;152&#93; An initiative to find a replacement for the SA80 family, known as [Project Grayburn](/Project_Grayburn), was in the concept phase in 2025, &#91;153&#93; and is expected to enter the assessment phase in 2026. &#91;154&#93;

The standard issue. The [L85A2/A3](/SA80), a workhorse. The constant quest for improvement, for upgrades, for that elusive perfect weapon. The [L403A1](/L403A1), a new addition, hinting at evolving tactical needs.

Some soldiers are equipped with the 7.62mm [L129A1 sharpshooter rifle](/L129A1), &#91;155&#93; which in 2018 formally replaced the [L86A2](/L86_LSW) Light Support Weapon. Support fire is provided by the [L7 general-purpose machine gun](/L7_(machine_gun)) (GPMG), &#91;156&#93; and indirect fire is provided by [L16 81mm mortars](/L16_81mm_mortar). Sniper rifles include the [L118A1](/Accuracy_International_Arctic_Warfare) 7.62 mm, [L115A3](/L115A3) and the [AW50F](/AW50F), all manufactured by [Accuracy International](/Accuracy_International). &#91;157&#93; The British Army utilises the [Glock 17](/Glock) as its side arm. &#91;151&#93;

The support weapons. The [L129A1](/L129A1), for precision. The [GPMG](/L7_(machine_gun)), a reliable workhorse. The sniper rifles, instruments of silent, deadly force. The ubiquitous [Glock 17](/Glock), a sidearm for close encounters.

Anti tank guided weapons include the [Javelin](/FGM-148_Javelin), the medium range anti-tank guided weapon replacement for [Milan](/MILAN), with overfly and direct attack modes of operation, and the [NLAW](/NLAW). The Next-generation Light Anti-tank Weapon ([NLAW](/NLAW)) is the first, non-expert, short-range, anti-tank missile that rapidly knocks out any main battle tank in just one shot by striking it from above. &#91;158&#93;

Anti-tank capabilities. The [Javelin](/FGM-148_Javelin) and [NLAW](/NLAW), modern weapons designed to neutralize armored threats. The emphasis on effectiveness, on taking out the target with precision.

##### Armour

The army's [main battle tank](/Main_battle_tank) is the [Challenger 2](/Challenger_2), which is being upgraded to [Challenger 3](/Challenger_3). &#91;159&#93; &#91;160&#93; It is supported by the [Warrior tracked armoured vehicle](/Warrior_tracked_armoured_vehicle) as the primary [infantry fighting vehicle](/Infantry_fighting_vehicle), &#91;161&#93; (which will soon be replaced by the [Boxer 8x8 armoured fighting vehicle](/Boxer_(armoured_fighting_vehicle))) and the [Bulldog armoured personnel carrier](/FV430_series). &#91;162&#93; The [Ajax armoured fighting vehicle](/General_Dynamics_Ajax) is also being brought into service. Light armoured units often utilise the [Supacat "Jackal" MWMIK](/MWMIK) and [Coyote](/Jackal_(vehicle)) tactical support vehicle for reconnaissance and fire support. &#91;163&#93;

The armored fist. The [Challenger 2](/Challenger_2), a formidable tank, undergoing modernization. The [Warrior](/Warrior_tracked_armoured_vehicle) and the incoming [Boxer](/Boxer_(armoured_fighting_vehicle)), for transporting and supporting infantry. The [Ajax](/General_Dynamics_Ajax), a new generation of reconnaissance vehicle. The agile [Jackal](/Jackal_(vehicle)) and [Coyote](/Jackal_(vehicle)), for speed and maneuverability.

##### Artillery

The army has three main artillery systems: the [M270 multiple launch rocket system](/M270_multiple_launch_rocket_system) (MLRS), the [Archer](/Archer_artillery_system) and the [L118 light gun](/L118_light_gun). &#91;164&#93; The MLRS, first used in [Operation Granby](/Operation_Granby), has an 85-kilometre (53 mi) standard range, or with the [PrSM](/Precision_Strike_Missile), up to 500 km. &#91;165&#93; The Archer is a 155 mm self-propelled armoured gun with a 50-kilometre (31 mi) range. The L118 light gun is a 105 mm towed gun, which is typically towed by a [Pinzgauer](/Steyr-Puch_Pinzgauer) all-terrain vehicle. &#91;166&#93; The army plans to replace the Archer with the [RCH 155](/RCH_155) in the near future. &#91;167&#93;

Fire support. The devastating power of the MLRS. The mobile [Archer](/Archer_artillery_system). The versatile [L118 light gun](/L118_light_gun). The continuous evolution of artillery systems, seeking greater range and precision.

To identify artillery targets, the army operates the TAIPAN artillery detection radar &#91;168&#93; and utilises [artillery sound ranging](/Artillery_sound_ranging). For air defence it uses the new [Sky Sabre](/Sky_Sabre) system, which in 2021 replaced the [Rapier](/Rapier_(missile)). &#91;170&#93; It also deploys the Very Short-Range Air Defence (VSHORAD) [Starstreak HVM](/Starstreak_(missile)) (high-velocity missile) launched by a single soldier or from a [Stormer HVM](/Alvis_Stormer) vehicle-mounted launcher. &#91;171&#93;

Target acquisition and air defence. The technology to detect and neutralize threats. The [Sky Sabre](/Sky_Sabre), a modern air defence system. The [Starstreak HVM](/Starstreak_(missile)), for immediate, close-in protection.

##### Protected mobility

Where armour is not required or mobility and speed are favoured the British Army utilises protected patrol vehicles, such as the Panther variant of the [Iveco LMV](/Iveco_LMV), the [Foxhound](/Ocelot_(vehicle)), and variants of the [Cougar](/Cougar_(MRAP)) family (such as the Ridgeback, Husky and Mastiff). &#91;172&#93; For day-to-day utility work the army commonly uses the [Land Rover Wolf](/Land_Rover_Wolf), which is based on the [Land Rover Defender](/Land_Rover_Defender). &#91;173&#93;

Vehicles designed for protection and speed. The [Panther](/Iveco_LMV), [Foxhound](/Ocelot_(vehicle)), and [Cougar](/Cougar_(MRAP)) variants. The ubiquitous [Land Rover Wolf](/Land_Rover_Wolf), a workhorse for everyday tasks.

##### Engineers, utility and signals

Specialist engineering vehicles include bomb-disposal robots such as the [T7 Multi-Mission Robotic System](/L3Harris) and the modern variants of the [Armoured Vehicle Royal Engineers](/Armoured_Vehicle_Royal_Engineers), including the Titan bridge-layer, [Trojan](/Trojan_Armoured_Vehicle_Royal_Engineers) armoured engineer vehicle, [Terrier armoured digger](/Terrier_armoured_digger). &#91;174&#93; Day-to-day utility work uses a series of support vehicles, including six-, nine- and fifteen-tonne [MAN](/MAN_Truck_%26_Bus) trucks, [Oshkosh](/Oshkosh_Corporation) heavy-equipment transporters (HET), close-support tankers, quad bikes and ambulances. &#91;175&#93; &#91;176&#93; Tactical communication uses the [Bowman](/Bowman_(communications_system)) radio system, and operational or strategic communication is controlled by the [Royal Corps of Signals](/Royal_Corps_of_Signals). &#91;177&#93;

The supporting arms. Engineers, logisticians, communicators. The vital infrastructure that enables the fighting force. The robots for bomb disposal, the bridge-layers, the heavy transport. The [Bowman](/Bowman_(communications_system)), the nervous system of the army.

##### Aviation

The [Army Air Corps](/British_Army_Air_Corps) (AAC) provides direct aviation support, with the [Royal Air Force](/Royal_Air_Force) providing support helicopters. The primary attack helicopter is the [Boeing AH-64E Apache](/AH-64E_Apache) which replaced the [AgustaWestland Apache AH-1](/AgustaWestland_Apache) in the anti-tank, anti-air defence, and anti-armour role. &#91;178&#93; The [AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat](/AgustaWestland_AW159_Wildcat) is a dedicated [intelligence, surveillance, target acquisition, and reconnaissance](/Intelligence,_surveillance,_target_acquisition,_and_reconnaissance) (ISTAR) helicopter. &#91;179&#93; The [Eurocopter AS 365N Dauphin](/Eurocopter_Dauphin) is used for [special operations](/Special_operations) aviation, primarily [counter terrorism](/Counterterrorism) operations, within the UK. &#91;180&#93; The army operates [unmanned aerial vehicles](/Unmanned_aerial_vehicle) in a surveillance role, such as the small [Lockheed Martin Desert Hawk III](/Lockheed_Martin_Desert_Hawk_III). &#91;181&#93; &#91;182&#93;

The air arm. The [Apache](/AH-64E_Apache) attack helicopter, a potent weapon. The [Wildcat](/AgustaWestland_AW159_Wildcat) for reconnaissance. The [Dauphin](/Eurocopter_Dauphin) for special operations. And the growing use of [unmanned aerial vehicles](/Unmanned_aerial_vehicle), the eyes in the sky.

